    "PLACE": "Position in the heavens, as of a heavenly body; -- usuallydefined by its right ascension and declination, or by its latitudeand longitude. Place of arms (Mil.), a place calculated for therendezvous of men in arms, etc., as a fort which affords a saferetreat for hospitals, magazines, etc. Wilhelm.-- High place (Script.), a mount on which sacrifices were offered.\"Him that offereth in the high place.\" Jer. xlviii. 35.-- In place, in proper position; timely.-- Out of place, inappropriate; ill-timed; as, his remarks were outof place.-- Place kick (Football), the act of kicking the ball after it hasbeen placed on the ground.-- Place name, the name of a place or locality. London Academy.-- To give place, to make room; to yield; to give way; to giveadvantage. \"Neither give place to the devil.\" Eph. iv. 27. \"Let allthe rest give place.\" Shak.-- To have place, to have a station, room, or seat; as, such desirescan have no place in a good heart.-- To take place. (a) To come to pass; to occur; as, the ceremonywill not take place. (b) To take precedence or priority. Addison. (c)To take effect; to prevail. \"If your doctrine takes place.\" Berkeley.\"But none of these excuses would take place.\" Spenser.-- To take the place of, to be substituted for.",
